----  # Constructor
* It is called automatically when you create an object.
* It has the same name as the class.
* It does not have a return type (not even `void`).

class Student {
    String name;
    // Constructor
    Student() { name = "Azmuddin";}
    void display() { System.out.println(name);  }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s1 = new Student(); // constructor called
        s1.display(); /// Azmuddin
    }
}
## 🔹 Types of Constructors
### 1. Default Constructor

* Provided by Java if you don’t write any constructor.
class Test {
    Test() {
        System.out.println("Default Constructor");
    }
}
### 2. Parameterized Constructor
* Takes arguments to initialize values.
class Student {
    String name;
    Student(String n) {
        name = n;
    }
}
Student s1 = new Student("Azmuddin");

### 3. Copy Constructor (not built-in, but created manually)

class Student {
    String name;
    Student(String n) {
        name = n;
    }
    Student(Student s) {
        name = s.name;
    }
}
## 🔹 Special Keyword: `this`
Used to refer to the current object.
class Student {
    String name;
    Student(String name) {
        this.name = name; // distinguishes variable
    }
}

---  # Static variable, method, block
the keyword **`static`** means something belongs to the **class**, not to individual object

 1. Static Variable (Class Variable)
A variable declared with `static` is **shared among all objects** of the class.

## 🔸 Key Points
* Only **one copy** exists (not per object)
* Memory is allocated **once in class area**
* Access using class name

class Student {
    static String college = "BVICAM"; // static variable
    String name;
    Student(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println(name + " " + college);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s1 = new Student("Azmuddin");
        Student s2 = new Student("Ali");

        s1.display();   /// Azmuddin BVICAM
        s2.display();   //// Ali BVICAM
    }
}
✔ Both objects share the same `college`

# 🔹 2. Static Method
A method declared with `static` can be called **without creating an object**.

## 🔸 Key Points
* Called using class name
* Can only directly access **static variables/methods**
* Cannot use `this` or `super`
class Demo {
    static void show() {
        System.out.println("Static method called");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo.show(); // no object needed
    }
}

# 🔹 3. Static Block
A block of code that runs **once when the class is loaded** (before `main()`).

## 🔸 Key Points
* Used for **initialization**
* Executes only once
* Runs before constructor and main method
class Test {
    static {
        System.out.println("Static block executed");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Main method");
    }
}
👉 Output:
Static block executed
Main method
# 🔥 Quick Comparison

| Feature        | Static Variable | Static Method     | Static Block     |
| -------------- | --------------- | ----------------- | ---------------- |
| Belongs to     | Class           | Class             | Class            |
| Object needed? | ❌ No            | ❌ No              | ❌ No             |
| Runs when      | Class loaded    | When called       | When class loads |
| Use            | Shared data     | Utility functions | Initialization   |

